    Replication of a research claim from Sandra and Otto (2018), Cognition 
Daniel C. Molden 
 
Project ID: Score Report - Sandra_Cognition_2018_0qar - Molden - Direct Replication - 20g 
OSF project: https://osf.io/w8xun/ 
Preregistration: https://osf.io/d9h62 
 
Claim Summary 
 
This replication tests the claim from Sandra and Otto (2018) that large reward incentives 
increase the amount of effort exerted by low-NFC (Need for Cognition) individuals for task-
switch costs but decrease the amount of effort exerted by high-NFC individuals. This reflects the 
following from the paper’s abstract: “[A] low intrinsic motivation to expend effort (measured by 
Need for Cognition)—predicted larger increase in cognitive effort expenditure in response to 
monetary reward incentives, while individuals...with greater intrinsic motivation to expend effort 
—were less responsive to reward incentives.” In the original paper, cognitive effort was 
operationalized in terms of performance on a switching task that required focused attention. The 
claim was tested using mixed-effects regression with regressors for the influence of trial type 
(task switch versus task repeat), reward level, experimental block, and Need for Cognition 
scores upon log transformed reaction times in the task-switching paradigm. 
 
Replication Criteria 
 
A successful replication of the key SCORE test (H*) would involve a significant three-
way interaction of trial-type, reward amount, and Need for Cognition, such that larger rewards 
increase performance on task-switch trials relative to task-repeat trials for low-NFC individuals, 
but this reward effect on performance does not occur for high-NFC individuals. 
 
 
Successful replication of preregistered H1 would involve a significant three-way 
interaction of trial-type, reward amount, and an executive function measure assessed by 
performance on a Stroop task, such that larger rewards increase performance on task-switch 
trials relative to task-repeat trials for low executive function individuals (i.e. individuals showing 
high levels of interference on the Stroop task), but this effect of reward on performance does not 
occur for high executive function individuals (i.e., individuals showing low levels of interference 
on the Stroop task). 
 
Successful replication of preregistered H2 would involve a significant a three-way 
interaction of trial-type, reward amount, and anticipated intrinsic motivation for the task-
switching activity as measured by an adapted version of the Intrinsic Motivation Inventory (e.g., 
Deci, Egharari, Patrick, & Leone, 1994) administered before the task was completed. Analogous 
to the findings for NFC, larger rewards should increase performance on task-switch trials 
relative to task-repeat trials for low-intrinsic-motivation individuals, but this effect should not 
occur for high-intrinsic-motivation individuals. 
 
Replication Result 
 
The replication included 127 participants in the analytic sample to reach the 
requirements for stage 1 data collection (N = 122). The focal test of H* resulted in a non-
significant Need for Cognition x trial-type x reward amount three-way interaction, ß = .0063, se = 
.0048, t = 1.336, p = .182. The focal test of H1 resulted in a non-significant Stroop interference x 
trial-type x reward amount three-way interaction, ß = -.0001, se = .0047, t = 0.14, p = .885. The 
focal test of H2 resulted in a non-significant intrinsic motivation x trial-type x reward amount 
three-way interaction, ß = .0001, se = .0048, t = 0.17, p = .865. The focal test did not replicate 

the original results and neither of the additional preregistered hypotheses were supported. Full 
output of the replication analyses can be found at: https://osf.io/w2egh/. 
 
 
One preregistered analysis did produce significant results. Using task accuracy as an 
alternative measure of task-switching costs, instead of reaction time for correct answers as in 
SCORE H*, a significant Need for Cognition x trial-type x reward amount three-way interaction 
was observed, b = -.074, se = .025, t = 2.993, p = .003. Follow up analyses further showed a 
significant negative interaction between trial-type and reward for those 1 SD above the mean in 
Need for Cognition, b = -.070, se = .034, t = 2.064, p = .039, such that the negative effect of 
switch versus repeat trials on accuracy was greater in the high reward versus the low reward 
condition for individuals higher in Need for Cognition. In contrast, these analyses showed a 
significant positive interaction between trial-type and reward for those 1 SD below the mean in 
Need for Cognition, b = .070, se = .034, t = 2.051, p = .040, such that the negative effect of 
switch versus repeat trials on accuracy was greater in the low reward versus the high reward 
condition for individuals lower in Need for Cognition. That is, individuals low in Need for 
Cognition appeared to expend more cognitive effort in the high reward condition, which reduced 
the negative effect of task-switching on accuracy, whereas individuals high in Need for 
Cognition appeared to expend more cognitive effort in the low reward condition. This pattern of 
results is consistent with the original claim. Full output of these analyses can be found at: 
https://osf.io/t7h9g/, pp. 1-3.  
 
 
The interpretation of these results in the original article was that the moderation by Need 
for Cognition reflected differences in intrinsic motivation for cognitive effort on the task, based 
on typical interpretations of individual differences in Need for Cognition. However, analyses of 
participants’ direct reports of their anticipated intrinsic motivation for performing well on the card-
sorting task did not similarly show a significant intrinsic motivation x trial-type x reward three-
way interaction on either reaction times for correct answers, ß = .0008, se = .0048, t = 0.171, p 
= .865, or task accuracy, b = .021, se = .022, t = 0.951, p = .341. This casts some doubt that the 
Need for Cognition results can be explained in terms of the direct intrinsic motivation 
experienced while completing the card-sorting task. Full output of these analyses can be found 
at: at: https://osf.io/t7h9g/, pp.10-11.  
 
Deviation from Preregistration 
Although the stage 1 results did not show a statistically significant effect at p < .05 for the 
focal H* test, stage 2 data collection was not conducted due to ending of Phase 1 of the SCORE 
project and the unavailability of the additional funds needed to conduct stage 2. 
 
The preregistration specified a sample size of 144 to achieve an analytic sample of 122 
based on the exclusion rate of the original study. Instead of recruiting all 144 participants and 
then excluding participants who did not meet the preregistered criteria, participants were 
informed of the exclusion criteria, which involved passing attention checks and meeting 
minimum performance criteria on the cognitive tasks administered, and told that if they did not 
meet these criteria they would be asked to “return” their survey or would have their submission 
“rejected” on the prolific.co platform so that a replacement participant could be recruited. 
Analyses of the attention checks and minimum performance criteria were then conducted in 
periodic batches while data collection was ongoing, and participant recruitment was continued 
until a minimum of 122 participants exceeded the exclusion thresholds in total. Therefore, 
although the stopping rule was not implemented exactly as preregistered, the same target 
analytic sample was recruited and none of the preregistered hypothesis tests were conducted 
until this analytic sample size was reached. 
 

As shown in the “prolific_export_exclusion.csv” file included with the raw data, a total of 
210 participants began the study. Of these, 68 participants returned the survey (either because 
they chose not to complete the study or did not meet the exclusion criteria), 10 participants had 
their responses rejected because they did not respond to a request to return their survey after 
not meeting exclusion criteria, and four participants had the survey “time-out” for exceeding the 
maximum time allotted by prolific.co without completing the study. This left 128 participants who 
met the performance criteria for inclusion in the study. When assembling the data for analysis, 
one additional participant was eliminated for incomplete responses on the questionnaire 
measures, leaving a final analytic sample of 127. Thus, overall, although the specific 
preregistered exclusion criteria were not altered, they were procedurally implemented in a 
different way than described in the preregistration. 
 
The pre-registered data-cleaning syntax mistakenly did not filter out the practice trials on 
the cardsort task before calculating the number of trials that timed out before participants could 
respond on the cardsort task. This mistake was corrected before the focal analyses were 
conducted. 
 
The pre-registered analysis syntax mistakenly failed to eliminate incorrect responses 
when analyzing the logRT variable on the card-sorting task, which was part of the preregistered 
procedures. The correction was made to the final analysis syntax. 
 
The pre-registered analysis syntax produces raw slope coefficients. To better match the 
standardized ßs reported at places in the original article, this syntax was updated to z-score 
individual difference measures (i.e., Need for Cognition and BAS) and continuous DVs (i.e., 
logRT) around the grand mean for the focal analyses. 
 
Description of Materials Provided 
 
All materials can be shared publicly 
 
Project IRB Materials – this folder includes all materials submitted to the local IRB and to the 
Human Research Protection Office (HRPO) of U.S. Army Medical Research and Development 
Command (USAMRDC). The files include the study protocol, consent forms and the certification 
to conduct human participants research for the principal investigator. The study was deemed to 
be exempt from further review. 
  
Methods and Materials – The Qualtrics Survey folder includes the specific items on the three 
individual difference questionnaires administered before the study via a Qualtrics survey and 
during the Inquisit program for the cognitive tasks. It also includes a viewable printout of the full 
survey in the Qualtrics_Survey.pdf file and the Sandra__Otto_Replication.qsv file that can be 
used to run the survey. 
 
The randomization.xlsx file details the randomized order of the trial types created for two blocks 
of the card-sorting task and the practice block. 
 
The Inquisit Program and Stimuli folder includes the materials needed to run the Stroop and 
card-sorting task blocks of the cognitive tasks. The README.docx file provides instructions on 
how to use the files to run the full experiment using Inquisit as detailed in the preregistered 
protocol. The Sanders_batch.iqx file launches the three trial blocks – Stroop task, rest video, 
card-sorting task. The stroop_Sanders.iqx file provides the code for the Stroop task and the 
cardsort.iqx file provides the code for the card-sorting task. The stroopinstructions1.htm and 

stroopinstructions2.htm files contain the instructions presented for the Stroop task. The 
correct.bmp and wrong.bmp files contain the feedback presented on correct and incorrect trials 
of the task. The switchinstructions1.htm, switchinstructions2.htm, and switchinstructions3.htm 
files contain the instructions presented for the card-sorting task. The lowreward.htm contain the 
instructions for the “low-reward” block and the highreward,htm contain the instructions for the 
“high-reward” block. The black2.bmp – black9.bmp contain the stimuli for the “black” trials on 
the card-sorting task and the red2.bmp – red9.bmp contain the stimuli for the “red” trials on the 
card-sorting task. The lowcorrect.bmp and highcorrect.bmp contain the feedback presented on 
correct trials of the “low-reward” and “high-reward” blocks of the task, respectively. Incorrect 
answers resulted in the same feedback from the wrong.bmp file as used for the Stroop task. 
The videoinstructions.htm file contains the instructions for the rest period between the two 
blocks of the card-sorting task where the rest_video.mp4 was presented, and the thanks.htm 
was the final screen participants saw at the end of the experiment. 
 
Data – the sandra_replicate.csv is the final data file assembled by the syntax in data cleaning 
syntax_Sandra_Congition_2018_0qar – Molden – Direct Replication.pdf from the files in the 
Raw Data folder: Sandra+&+Otto_Replication_May+10+2021_NCOG and BISBAS.csv, 
sandra_replication_cardsort_raw_21_05_10.csv, 
sandra_replication_cardsort_summary_21_05_10.csv, 
sandra_replication_cardsort_survey_intrinsic_motivation_21_05_10.csv, 
sandra_replication_stroop_sandra_raw_21_05_10.csv, 
sandra_replication_stroop_sandra_summary_21_05_10.csv, blocknumber.csv, order1.csv, and 
order2.csv. The remaining file in that folder, prolific_export_exclusion.csv contains data on the 
number of participants who began the study and either did not complete it or did not meet 
exclusion criteria. 
 
The Transformed Data folder contains the intermediate data matrices created by the data 
cleaning syntax_Sandra_Congition_2018_0qar – Molden – Direct Replication.pdf to assemble 
the final sandra_replicate.csv data set. 
 
Analysis - analysis syntax_Sandra_Cognition_2018_0qar - Molden - Direct Replication - 
20g.pdf provides the analysis syntax for the focal H* SCORE hypothesis, as well as the other 
preregistered hypotheses. The follow-up analyses listed were only performed if the 
hypothesized interaction effects were significant at the p < .05 level. The syntax utilizes the 
sandra_replicate.csv data set. H*analysis output_Sandra_Cognition_2018_0qar - Molden - 
Direct Replication - 20g.pdf provides the full output of the focal SCORE H*analysis. 
H1_H2_analysis output_Sandra_Cognition_2018_0qar - Molden - Direct Replication - 20g.pdf 
provides the full output of the additional preregistered analyses. 
 
Preregistered Materials – Preregistration_final_Sandra_Cognition_2018_0qar - Molden - 
Direct Replication - 20g.pdf details the full preregistration for the study. The Data_cleaning 
syntax.pdf and Data_analysis_syntax.pdf contains the preregistered data_cleaning and analysis 
syntax. The Simulation for preregistration folder contains simulated data used to test the data 
cleaning and analysis syntax. 
 
Citation: Sandra, D. A., & Otto, A. R. (2018). Cognitive capacity limitations and Need for 
Cognition differentially predict reward-induced cognitive effort expenditure. Cognition, 172, 101-
